Okay, seems like I found the problem. Apparently adapter Fetch was sending the requests with `'Transfer-Encoding': 'chunked'` header and `'Content-Length': ''`. 
So I created Axios interceptor:

```ts
	axiosInstance.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
		if (config.data && typeof config.data === "object") {
			const jsonData = JSON.stringify(config.data);
			config.data = jsonData;
			config.headers["Content-Length"] = Buffer.byteLength(jsonData).toString();
			config.headers["Content-Type"] = "application/json";
		}
		return config;
	});
```

Hope this helps. 🔥

Hi, we are facing the same issue in `1.8.4`. 

Here is our code: https://github.com/SAP/ai-sdk-js/blob/813083840cc2809efbb18f7ad0d218d99d1fc4de/packages/orchestration/src/orchestration-client.ts#L138

So we set `responseType` to `stream` and it works well if remote responds with 2xx. However, in case of a 400 (or similar), even when remote just returns an `application/json` with a JSON error object, the `error.response.data` is a stream object and we need to for await through it to get the full response body. 

Here is our workaround to get the full error response body:

```ts
try {
    // Send a post request with `responseType: stream`
  } catch (error: any) {
    if (
      error.config.responseType === 'stream' &&
      error.response?.data &&
      typeof error.response.data.read === 'function'
    ) {
      const chunks: Buffer[] = [];
      // `error.response.data` is a stream object instead of a complete JSON object
      for await (const chunk of error.response.data) {
        chunks.push(Buffer.isBuffer(chunk) ? chunk : Buffer.from(chunk));
      }
      error.response.data = JSON.parse(Buffer.concat(chunks).toString('utf8'));
    }
    throw error;
  }
```

We would appreciate it if Axios can return error response data directly when using streaming instead of returning buffer chunks of body.

