As a workaround, I was able to force webpack to load the CommonJS version of my package. It works because it finds the `axios.default` instance which the CJS version of Axios exposes.

I achieved this using `resolve.alias` in the `webpack.config.js` file of the consuming app (see https://webpack.js.org/configuration/resolve/#resolvealias):

```js
const path = require('path');

module.exports = {
  //...
  resolve: {
    alias: {
      mylib: require.resolve('mylib'),
    },
  },
};
```

`require.resolve('mylib')` resolves to the CJS file as per the `package.json` exports in `mylib`.

It works, but I really don't like the solution as it's not practical (consumer shouldn't have to worry about this).

Looking at the other open issues, I think axios needs to improve the way the package is bundled (stop default export? re-export the instance via a named export? fix exports in package.json to point to the appropriate dist file instead of the root index.js?publish a new axios-es package?)

I found another workaround when bundling with `tsup`. I think `tsup` itself is having issues with `default` exports in CJS modules.

In order to avoid these issues (`axios__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__.create is not a function` instead of `axios__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__.default.create`), I ended up bundling `axios` with my package using this `tsup` config:

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from 'tsup';

export default defineConfig({
  // ...
  noExternal: ['axios'],
});
```

I also needed to patch `axios`'s `exports` using [pnpm patch](https://pnpm.io/cli/patch) to work around #5495:

```
diff --git a/package.json b/package.json
index a759d02f4d66c5cf834f0e291020b062ac9cabf7..1a13ebbbd79fc15fba8799158c498c3b1f695e16 100644
--- a/package.json
+++ b/package.json
@@ -11,11 +11,11 @@
       },
       "browser": {
         "require": "./dist/browser/axios.cjs",
-        "default": "./index.js"
+        "default": "./dist/esm/axios.js"
       },
       "default": {
         "require": "./dist/node/axios.cjs",
-        "default": "./index.js"
+        "default": "./dist/esm/axios.js"
       }
     },
     "./lib/adapters/http.js": "./lib/adapters/http.js",
``` 

Again, this is not ideal and it's only a workaround. But that's when you get when using `default` exports 😢

