> Is there any way to configure Axios to send headers in a case-sensitive manner, or is there a workaround to address this issue? Any insights or suggestions would be greatly appreciated!

Yeah. The `AxiosHeaders` class used by Axios internally preserves the case of headers. This means that after setting a new header (that was not there before as an object property) Axios won't change its case
```js
import {AxiosHeaders} from 'axios';

const headers = new AxiosHeaders({
  FOO: undefined // just a case preset
});

headers.set({
  'foo': 'fooValue', // it is still FOO
  'bar': 'barValue'
});

console.log(headers.toJSON()); // [Object: null prototype] { FOO: 'fooValue', bar: 'barValue' }

// alternative
console.log(AxiosHeaders.concat({
  FOO: undefined
}, {
  'foo': 'fooValue',
  'bar': 'barValue'
}).toJSON());

// Axios do this internally to resolve headers configuration (pseudo code)
const resolvedHeadersForAdapter = AxiosHeaders.concat(
  instance.defaults.headers.common,
  instance.defaults.headers.post, // method specific
  instance.defaults.headers
  request.headers
)
```
Thus, you can create a preset of headers with the desired cases in the instance configuration and Axios will respect it.

```js
const instance = axios.create();

instance.defaults.headers.common = {
  'content-type': undefined,
  accept: 'application/json, text/plain, */*',
  'user-agent': undefined,
  'content-length': undefined,
  AnyCaseYouWant: undefined
}

const {data} = await instance.post(url, 'foo');
```

