Hello @0xF5T9,
The simplest, most intended and type-safe way is this:

```
import axios, { AxiosResponse } from "axios";

interface RegisterRequest {
  email: string;
  username: string;
  password: string;
}

interface RegisterResponse {
  token: string;
  userId: string;
}

const result = await axios.post<RegisterResponse>(
  "/register",
  {
    email: "user@example.com",
    username: "testuser",
    password: "12345",
  } satisfies RegisterReques
);

const data: RegisterResponse = result.data;
```

- The generic argument <RegisterResponse> tells Axios what the response type is.
- The satisfies RegisterRequest keyword (new in TypeScript 4.9) ensures the request body matches the RegisterRequest interface.

**Why the StackOverflow Snippet Works**
This snippet
```
axios.post<AuthResponse, AxiosResponse<AuthResponse, TBody>, TBody>(
  "theurl",
  { grant_type: "x", refresh_token: "y" }
);
```
works because:
Axios’s post() actually has this signature:

```
post<T = any, R = AxiosResponse<T>, D = any>(
  url: string,
  data?: D,
  config?: AxiosRequestConfig<D>
): Promise<R>;
```
So the 3 generics mean:
T → response data type
R → full AxiosResponse type (you can override it if you want)
D → request data type

That’s why their <AuthResponse, AxiosResponse<AuthResponse, TBody>, TBody> works, even if it looks messy.

