this is expected behaviour, not a bug. axios intentionally decodes certain characters in the URL for RFC 3986 compliance.

if you need consistent encoding, you can provide a custom paramsSerializer:
```
const response = await httpClient.get('https://example.com/api/test', {
  params: {
    filter: { EstimatedStartedAt: "2025-01-23" },
    OrderType: 'asc',
  },
  paramsSerializer: (params) => {
    return new URLSearchParams(
      Object.entries(params).map(([k, v]) => [k, typeof v === 'object' ? JSON.stringify(v) : v])
    ).toString();
  }
});
```

this will give you full control over the encoding. however, note that your API should handle both encoded and unencoded characters since both are valid per RFC 3986.

Hi @j-mew-s,

The issue occurs because `jsdom` uses the 'xhr' adapter by default, while `node` uses the 'http' adapter.

To resolve this, you can configure axios to use the 'http' adapter in your project like this:

```javascript
const instance = axios.create({
  baseURL: 'https://localhost:3000',
  httpsAgent: new https.Agent({
    rejectUnauthorized: false
  }),
  adapter: 'http',
});
```

Axios currently autodetects only browser (xhr) and Node (http) adapters. In Deno, it incorrectly falls back to the Node HTTP adapter, which causes runtime errors such as:

TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'write')


sets the adapter to 'fetch' explicitly in Deno environments:

const req = axios.create({
  adapter: 'fetch',
  baseURL: 'http://0.0.0.0',
});


This ensures Axios uses a compatible adapter in Deno while preserving existing behavior in Node and browser environments.

