Hi @BangDori 
I don’t believe this is a responsibility that should fall on the Axios library itself.

In your case, you have a business rule that requires all GET requests to use the same timeout. However, other users might have different timeout values even for the same HTTP verb. Because of this variability, Axios should remain generic and flexible, rather than enforcing behavior based on method types.

To handle your specific need, I suggest creating separate Axios instances, each with its own configuration. For example:

```js
const forGetInstanceOnly = axios.create({ timeout: 3000 });
const forPostInstanceOnly = axios.create({ timeout: 10000 });

export const get = forGetInstanceOnly.get;
export const post = forPostInstanceOnly.post;
```

This approach keeps your logic clean and outside of Axios, ensuring that the library stays generic and unopinionated, so it can support a wide range of use cases without enforcing specific business rules.

