It is not an expected behaviour but a design flaw more or less. Upon exploring the issue in depth i found that for synchronous requests it does behave as  @BoubleJ wants. But for asynchronus interceptors it behaves differently. This inconsistency can come across as a bug to the users.

## Example  (Asynchronous Interceptors):

```
const onRequest = () => {
  console.log("onRequestTriggered");
  throw new Error("Error");
};

const onRequestError = (err) => {
  console.log(`Request : ${err.message}`);
};

const onResponse = () => {
  console.log("onResponseTriggered");
};

const onResponseError = (err) => {
  console.log(`Resposne : ${err.message}`);
};
axios.interceptors.request.use(onRequest, onRequestError, {
  synchronous: false, // which is the default behavior
});
axios.interceptors.response.use(onResponse, onResponseError, {
  synchronous: false, // which is the default behavior
}); 
```

You see this 

```
onRequestTriggered
Resposne : Error
```

## Example (Synchronous Interceptors)
```
const onRequest = () => {
  console.log("onRequestTriggered");
  throw new Error("Error");
};

const onRequestError = (err) => {
  console.log(`Request : ${err.message}`);
};

const onResponse = () => {
  console.log("onResponseTriggered");
};

const onResponseError = (err) => {
  console.log(`Resposne : ${err.message}`);
};
axios.interceptors.request.use(onRequest, onRequestError, {
  synchronous: true, //overriding default behaviour
});
axios.interceptors.response.use(onResponse, onResponseError, {
  synchronous: true, //overriding default behaviour
});
```

You see this
```
onRequestTriggered
Request : Error
Resposne : Request failed with status code 405 
```


So even if it is intendend behaviour this inconsistency is not good for developer experience.

