The `MaxListenersExceededWarning` still occurs when a single request follows ≥ 11 redirects.

**Root cause**

With `follow-redirects`, each redirect hop creates a new underlying `ClientRequest` (new socket), but the outer `RedirectableRequest` is **reused** across the entire chain. Every hop fires the `socket` event → `handleRequestSocket` → `req.once('close', clearCurrentReq)`, stacking a new listener onto the same `RedirectableRequest` without removing the previous one. With 11 hops the count exceeds Node.js's default limit of 10.

**Reproduction** (`node --trace-warnings repro.js`, axios 1.15.2)

```js
const http = require('http');
const axios = require('axios');

const REDIRECT_COUNT = 11;

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  const match = req.url.match(/^\/redirect\/(\d+)$/);
  if (match) {
    const n = Number(match[1]);
    if (n < REDIRECT_COUNT) {
      res.writeHead(302, { Location: `/redirect/${n + 1}` });
    } else {
      res.writeHead(200, { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' });
      res.end(JSON.stringify({ redirects: n }));
    }
    res.end();
    return;
  }
  res.writeHead(302, { Location: '/redirect/1' });
  res.end();
});

server.listen(0, '127.0.0.1', async () => {
  const { port } = server.address();
  console.log('axios version:', axios.VERSION);
  try {
    const res = await axios.get(`http://127.0.0.1:${port}/start`);
    console.log('Response:', res.data);
  } finally {
    server.close();
  }
});
```

